@startuml fig-cors-preflight
skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center

title CORS Preflight — Why It Works in Postman but Not in the Browser

participant "Browser\n(origin: app.com)" as B #FFE0B2
participant "API Server\n(origin: api.com)" as S #C8E6C9

== Preflight (automatic OPTIONS request) ==

B -[#FF9800]> S : OPTIONS /api/users\nOrigin: https://app.com\nAccess-Control-Request-Method: PUT\nAccess-Control-Request-Headers: Authorization

alt Server allows the origin
  S -[#43A047]-> B : 204 No Content\nAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: https://app.com\nAccess-Control-Allow-Methods: GET, PUT, DELETE\nAccess-Control-Allow-Headers: Authorization\nAccess-Control-Max-Age: 3600
else Server rejects the origin
  S -[#E53935]-> B : 204 (missing Allow-Origin)\nor 403 Forbidden
  note right of B
    Browser blocks the actual
    request entirely.
  end note
end

|||

== Actual Request (only if preflight succeeded) ==

B -[#1565C0]> S : PUT /api/users/3\nOrigin: https://app.com\nAuthorization: Bearer ...
S -[#43A047]-> S : process request
S -[#43A047]-> B : 200 OK\nAccess-Control-Allow-Origin: https://app.com

legend right
  CORS is a browser security policy, not a server one.
  Postman and curl skip preflight entirely.
  Non-simple methods (PUT, DELETE) or custom headers
  trigger the automatic OPTIONS check.
endlegend
@enduml
